article.description:
Ray Allen had 35 points, including a 3-pointer with 1:16 remaining, as the Milwaukee Bucks took advantage of Tracy McGrady's absence to defeat the Orlando Magic
108-103 Monday night.
article.headline: Without McGrady again, Magic fall
article.linkText: Allen pours in 35 to lead Bucks over wounded Magic
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Milwaukee's Ray Allen hid the pain in his ankles rather well against Orlando.
Allen

Allen had 35 points on 12-of-22 shooting, adding six rebounds and six assists to lead the Bucks past the Magic 108-103 Monday night. "I have arthritic pain in my ankles,'' Allen said. "The right one, I already had it (the pain) in there but the left one's starting to act up. It feels like my ankles are just locking up.'' It was Allen's clutch shooting that locked up Milwaukee's second win in its last five games. Every time Orlando threatened down the stretch, Allen responded. Mike Miller's free throws brought the Magic to 97-95 with 1:44 remaining in the game, but Allen hit a 3-pointer 28 seconds later. Shawn Kemp followed Miller's free throws with two more, making Milwaukee's lead 100-97 with 1:10 left. Allen then hit an off-balance shot to put the Bucks up by five points with 47.3 seconds remaining. Milwaukee converted six more free throws while the Magic hit a couple of meaningless 3-pointers, missing seven other shots in the game's final 1:27. For the quarter, Orlando shot 9-of-27. "It was a great Christmas present,'' Bucks coach George Karl said of the victory. "Kind of spirit-lifting to us.'' Orlando was without its spirit, missing leading scorer Tracy McGrady for the third time in the past four games. McGrady is expected to return for a Christmas Day game with Detroit after sitting out to rest a lower back bruise he sustained Dec. 10 against the Lakers. Miller had with 29 points and Grant Hill 27 but it wasn't enough. "There's certain teams that you need your leading scorer against, and when you're playing the No. 2 offense in the NBA, you need every bullet you can get,'' Magic coach Doc Rivers said. "Grant and Mike were phenomenal and so was Darrell (Armstrong). "We just didn't get a lot of offense anywhere else. We just didn't have a lot of other places to turn.'' Allen found a support system in Bucks reserve Michael Redd, who had 20 points and 11 rebounds, and Sam Cassell scored 19. Anthony Mason had a season-best 18 and the Bucks converted 31 of 36 free throws. After dropping three in a row, the Bucks hope they have momentum with a two-game win streak. The team plays three of its next four on the road. "These situations we've been in lately have been fun because we've learned a lot about each other,'' Allen said. "This is a team that's been new to each other, so we've been learning what we're going to give and get from each other. It's starting to come to fruition, how we're going to play basketball.'' A 3-pointer by Allen at 4:38 left put the Bucks in the lead at 90-89 for the first time since early in the third quarter. Orlando got the lead back on a pair of free throws by Hill, but the Magic never led again. Game notes
Iran Brown, the 13-year-old boy wounded by the D.C.-area sniper, was a special guest of McGrady at the game. ... Milwaukee has won 12 of the last 14 meetings with Orlando. ... The Bucks' Jason Caffey missed his third consecutive game with a right pinkie. ... Kemp was called for a flagrant 1 foul in second quarter. Cassell missed both free-throw attempts. ... The Magic surpassed 100 points for only the fifth time in the past 23 regular-season games against Milwaukee.
